# p. 360
Macbeth <- grepl(" MACBETH\\.", macbeth)
LadyMacbeth <- grepl(" LADY MACBETH\\.", macbeth) 
Banquo <- grepl(" BANQUO\\.", macbeth) 
Duncan <- grepl(" DUNCAN\\.", macbeth)
# p. 360
speaker_freq <- data.frame(Macbeth, LadyMacbeth, Banquo, Duncan) %>%
  mutate(line = 1:length(macbeth)) %>%
  gather(key = "character", value = "speak", -line) %>% 
  mutate(speak = as.numeric(speak)) %>%
  filter(line > 218 & line < 3172)

acts_idx <- grep("^ACT [I|V]+", macbeth)

  ylab("Proportion of Speeches")

# p. 364
Corpus <- with(DataSciencePapers, VCorpus(VectorSource(abstract))) 
Corpus[[1]] %>%
  as.character() %>% 
  strwrap()
[1] "Astronomy is one of the most data-intensive of the sciences. Data technology is"            
[2] "accelerating the quality and effectiveness of its research, and the rate of astronomical"   
[3] "discovery is higher than ever. As a result, many view astronomy as being in a 'Golden Age',"
[4] "and projects such as the Virtual Observatory are amongst the most ambitious data projects"  
[5] "in any field of science. But these powerful tools will be impotent unless the data on which"
[6] "they operate are of matching quality. Astronomy, like other fields of science, therefore"   
[7] "needs to establish and agree on a set of guiding principles for the management of"          
[8] "astronomical data. To focus this process, we are constructing a 'data manifesto', which"    
[9] "proposes guidelines to maximise the rate and cost-effectiveness of scientific discovery."   
# p. 364
Corpus <- Corpus %>% 
  tm_map(stripWhitespace) %>%
  tm_map(removeNumbers) %>%
  tm_map(removePunctuation) %>%
  tm_map(content_transformer(tolower)) %>%
  tm_map(removeWords, stopwords("english"))
strwrap(as.character(Corpus[[1]]))
